Certainly! Here's an example Java code that implements IoC without using any framework like Spring Boot:

```
interface Service {
  void execute();
}

class ServiceA implements Service {
  @Override
  public void execute() {
    System.out.println("Executing service A");
  }
}

class ServiceB implements Service {
  @Override
  public void execute() {
    System.out.println("Executing service B");
  }
}

class Client {
  private final Service service;

  Client(Service service) {
    this.service = service;
  }

  public void executeService() {
    service.execute();
  }
}

public class Main {
  public static void main(String[] args) {
    Service service = new ServiceB();
    Client client = new Client(service);
    client.executeService();
  }
}
```

This code defines three classes: `Service`, `ServiceA`, and `ServiceB`. `Service` is an interface that declares a single method `execute()`. Both `ServiceA` and `ServiceB` implement the `Service` interface and implement the `execute()` method in their own way.

There is also a `Client` class that has a dependency on `Service`. The `Service` object is passed to the `Client` object's constructor, using constructor injection. `Client` has a method `executeService()` that simply calls the `execute()` method of the injected `Service` object.

Finally, in the `main()` method, we create a `ServiceB` object and pass it to the `Client` constructor, which in turn calls the `executeService()` method. This demonstrates how the `Client` class is decoupled from the concrete implementation of the `Service` interface. In other words, the control of creating the `Service` object is inverted from the `Client` class to the `main()` method, which helps with testing and flexibility.

I hope this example helps you understand the concept of IoC!

To query a database in Spring Boot, you can use Spring Data JPA. Spring Data JPA is a framework that provides an abstraction layer on top of JPA (Java Persistence API), which is a standard for working with databases in Java. With Spring Data JPA, you can write repository interfaces (also known as DAOs) that include methods to retrieve, update, and delete data from the database. Spring Data JPA will generate the necessary SQL queries based on the method names and annotations.

Here's an example of how to define a repository interface that extends the `JpaRepository` interface and includes a method to retrieve data from the database:

```
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.JpaRepository;

public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {

    User findByUsername(String username);

}
```

In this example, `User` is an entity class that represents a table in the database, and `Long` is the type of the primary key for the `User` table. The `findByUsername()` method is used to retrieve a user by their username.

To use this repository in your Spring Boot application, you simply need to inject an instance of the `UserRepository` interface into your code and use it to retrieve data from the database:

```
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;

public class UserService {

    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    public User getUserByUsername(String username) {
        return userRepository.findByUsername(username);
    }

}
```

In this example, `UserService` is a service class that retrieves a user from the database using the `UserRepository`. The `@Autowired` annotation tells Spring to inject an instance of the `UserRepository` interface into the `userRepository` field.

Note that in order to use Spring Data JPA, you need to configure the database connection settings in the `application.properties` file or a similar configuration file. The default configuration uses Hibernate as the JPA implementation, but you can also customize the JPA implementation and other settings as needed.

No, the details of the connection to the database (such as the JDBC URL, username, password, etc.) are typically not provided by a service class in Spring Boot. Instead, Spring Boot provides a number of mechanisms for externalizing configuration details like database connection settings, and it relies on IoC to inject the necessary configuration values into the relevant parts of the application.

One common way to provide database connection details in Spring Boot is to use the `application.properties` file or a similar configuration file to specify the connection settings. For example, you might include the following lines in your `application.properties` file:

```
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=create
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb
spring.datasource.username=dbuser
spring.datasource.password=dbpass
```

In this example, the `spring.datasource` properties specify the JDBC URL, username, and password for the database connection, and the `spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto` property specifies how the schema should be created or updated.

Spring Boot uses IoC to inject these configuration values into the relevant parts of the application. For example, when you define a `DataSource` bean in your application context, Spring Boot will automatically configure it with the database connection settings specified in the configuration file:

```
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.jdbc.datasource.DriverManagerDataSource;

import javax.sql.DataSource;

@Configuration
public class AppConfig {

    @Bean
    public DataSource dataSource() {
        DriverManagerDataSource dataSource = new DriverManagerDataSource();
        dataSource.setDriverClassName("com.mysql.jdbc.Driver");
        dataSource.setUrl("jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb");
        dataSource.setUsername("dbuser");
        dataSource.setPassword("dbpass");
        return dataSource;
    }
}
```

In this example, the `dataSource()` method returns a new instance of `DriverManagerDataSource`, which is configured with the database connection settings specified in the `application.properties` file. Spring Boot uses IoC to inject this `DataSource` bean into other parts of the application that require database access.

By separating the configuration details from the service classes and using IoC to inject the necessary dependencies, Spring Boot makes it easier to manage and maintain the application, and also makes it easier to test and modify the application's behavior.

